<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORDS AND RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I believe that Professor Kwaku Person-Lynn (Voices, Nov. 28, "Language Keeps 
Racism Alive") had something of value to say. However, his manipulation of word 
definitions was truly outrageous. 
</P>
<P>
 To begin with, word processor programs do not provide extensive word 
definitions with the many variable meanings that exist in the English language. 
</P>
<P>
 Secondly, when I turned to my dictionary (The Concise Oxford English 
Dictionary) to see how it defined ethnic I was given the following: 
</P>
<P>
 1. a. (of a social group) having a common national or cultural tradition, b. 
(of clothes, etc.) resembling those of a non-European exotic people 
</P>
<P>
 2. denoting origin by birth or descent rather than by nationality (ethnic 
Turks) 
</P>
<P>
 3. relating to race or culture (ethnic group; ethnic origins) 
</P>
<P>
 4 (archaic) pagan, heathen 
</P>
<P>
 In order to control our language we have to be aware of its origins. It is 
imperative that we know ethnic once meant a heathen person so we can ensure 
that it never happen again. Person-Lynn is just as guilty with his manipulation 
of word meanings to validate his argument as those who use language to demean 
and control others. 
</P>
<P>
 NANCY PERRY 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Monica 
</P>
</TEXT>
