</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council today will hear an appeal of a recent Planning Commission 
decision that rejected an application for an expanded day-care center. 
</P>
<P>
 In a 4-to-1 vote last month, the commission voted against the center and said 
the neighborhood site had too few curbside parking places. 
</P>
<P>
 Carman Altamirano, who lives and works at 28885 Woodcreek, had been allowed to 
watch over six children. 
</P>
<P>
 When she wanted to expand her business to care for as many as 12 children, 
several neighbors complained about the potential danger extra traffic might 
create for their children. 
</P>
<P>
 Commissioners argued that Altamirano's home is on a cul-de-sac where there is 
little curbside parking. 
</P>
<P>
 Other city officials had recommended approving the application, saying the 
expansion would create little extra traffic. FRANK MESSINA 
