<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE HUNGER WARS; SCHOOLS WITHOUT BREAKFAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One hundred ninety-three schools in six Southern California counties should 
begin a breakfast program because they have so many low-income children, the 
California Department of Education says. In these schools, 40% or more of the 
students would qualify for a free or reduced-price meal, subsidized by the 
federal government. Numerous studies say breakfast programs significantly 
improve children's health and ability to learn, but many school officials say 
the logistic barriers can be overwhelming. LOS ANGELES COUNTY 
